\f + \fr 18:1\ft Reproach. True friendship resembles charity, and bears all things, 1 Corinthians 13:4. Hebrew now reads Thave, "desire;" instead of Thuane, occasion, or "pretext," which must have been in the copies of the Septuagint and Vulgate. (Calmet) --- Protestants, "through desire, a man having separated himself, seeketh and intermeddleth with all wisdom." The solitary seeks heaven. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 18:2\ft Heart. Conformable to his passions. (Calmet) --- Hebrew, "unless to lay open his heart." He wishes to appear wise, and to justify his wicked designs. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 18:3\ft Contemneth both God and man, Luke 18:4. Hebrew, "is contemned" in his turn. (Calmet) --- He is like a man abandoned by the physician. (Op. Imp. in Matt. Hom. 40.)\f*
\f + \fr 18:4\ft Man, who is just and wise. His advice deserves attention, Proverbs 20:5.\f*
\f + \fr 18:6\ft Quarrels. Hebrew, "blows." Septuagint, "death;" (ver. 7.) which are the usual consequences of quarrels.\f*
\f + \fr 18:8\ft Tongued. Hebrew, "calumniator." He pretends to wish well to those of whom he speaks, or else to guard the company against deceit. (Calmet) --- "If the devil be upon the detractor's tongue, he is in the ears of those who pay attention to him." (St. Francis de Sales) --- Fear, etc., is in the Septuagint, above. The Vulgate retains both this and the new version of St. Jerome.\f*
\f + \fr 18:9\ft Brother. Like him, as both end in poverty, Proverbs 10:4., and 12:11.\f*
\f + \fr 18:10\ft Name. Essence, or protection of God. The rich depends on his own wealth.\f*
\f + \fr 18:13\ft Heareth the end of the question, Proverbs 1:5.\f*
\f + \fr 18:14\ft Infirmity of the flesh, Matthew 26:41. --- That is. Theodotion, "is wounded, who shall support?"\f*
\f + \fr 18:16\ft Princes. He easily finds access by showing submission. (Calmet) Placatur donis Jupiter ipse suis. (Ovid)\f*
\f + \fr 18:17\ft Him. To see that he act with sincerity.\f*
\f + \fr 18:18\ft Lot. Proverbs 16:33. Septuagint, "silence." (Calmet) --- But Grabe substitutes "lot." (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 18:19\ft Judgments of many are more deserving of credit. Hebrew, "a brother offended, is like a strong place, and their quarrels," etc. They are not easily reconciled. Civil wars are most terrible. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 18:20\ft Satisfied. Those who are guarded in their words get employment. (Haydock) (Chap. 12:14.)\f*
\f + \fr 18:21\ft Love it, and speak well or ill, shall receive accordingly, Matthew 12:37.\f*
\f + \fr 18:22\ft Good wife. Good is not in Hebrew, but should be understood, as it is expressed in the Complutensian (Calmet) and Alexandrian Septuagint. (Haydock) --- He that, etc., occurs not in Hebrew, Sixtus V, etc. But it is found in Septuagint and Arabic. The Syriac omits the last sentence. --- Wicked. St. Augustine had frequently asserted that a divorce was only of counsel: but this he retracted, when he reflected on this text. (Retractions 1:19.) --- The Hebrews, Athenians, and Romans, followed the same practice with adulteresses. (Selden, Ux. 3:16.; Dem. in Neaeram, etc.) --- Hermas (past. 1:4.) prescribes that the penitent shall be received again, but not often. In case of divorce, the fathers still permit not a second marriage, that the parties may be reconciled. They enjoin the husband to put away only such as are incorrigible. (St. Augustine, Adul. 2:3.) (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 18:24\ft Brother. The ties of nature are not so strong as those of friendship. (Calmet) --- Hebrew, "a man that hath friends must shew himself friendly; and there is a friend that sticketh closer than a brother." (Protestants) (Haydock) --- Ut ameris ama. (Martial)\f*
