\f + \fr 28:1\ft Pursueth. "A crime is its own punishment." (Seneca, ep. 93.) (Leviticus 26:36.) --- Dread. Of any thing terrestrial, as long as the object of his love is not attacked, Romans 8:35.\f*
\f + \fr 28:2\ft Princes. Who each contend for the sovereign power. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 28:8\ft Poor. It seldom happens that the unjust leave their riches to their children, Proverbs 13:22., and Job 27:16.\f*
\f + \fr 28:9\ft His. Septuagint, "he rendereth his prayer abominable."\f*
\f + \fr 28:13\ft Mercy. This is true repentance, which enjoins, "not only to bewail past sins, but also to amend." (St. Ambrose, 2:Pen. v.) --- Sacramental confession was not required of the Jews, but they confessed their sins, when they laid their hands on the victim, etc., Leviticus 4., and 5. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 28:16\ft Prudence. Septuagint, "riches." Poverty is a great temptation to people in authority, more than avarice itself. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 28:20\ft Innocent. Unpunished, if he employ fraud, ver. 22., and Proverbs 13:21.\f*
\f + \fr 28:21\ft Forsaketh. Hebrew, "oppresseth (Septuagint, selleth) a man." (Calmet) --- Neither small nor great bribes must be taken. (Justinian)\f*
\f + \fr 28:22\ft Poverty. Septuagint, "the merciful shall have power over him," ver. 8. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 28:28\ft Men. Septuagint, "the just groan," and all are under "apprehensions." (Calmet)\f*
